<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-519-398  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 519 398.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 14 1989 v23 n33 p61(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Selling big IS projects to the boss. (information systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ryan, Alan J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The process of obtaining high-level approval for long-termfactory-floor MIS projects requires intensive background researchand an effort to 'sell' new technology to executives.andP;  Researchfor a major project can take as long as two years, involving studyof goals and objectives, as well as how the project will affectworkers.andP;  Careful examination of the proposed project may revealways it can be simplified before automation takes place, andbreaking the project down makes it easier to justify.andP;  A soundanalysis provides a firm foundation for presenting the project toexecutives as well as a clear understanding of the benefitsinvolved.andP;  Top-level management can then appreciate the methodsthat will move the company toward new technology.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ManufacturingFactory ManagementManagement-EDP RelationsMISExecutive.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>